#: 9e010b8891e14536859cb86ba76d15c0
msgid "How to use block storage devices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:6
#: 5d87c87628404dbb88a257b41e67e73c
msgid ""
"*This page is part of* :doc:`device handling in qubes </user/how-to-"
"guides/how-to-use-devices>` *.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:8
#: e71ee70fab88435b86aec5ebafdfe732
msgid ""
"If you don’t know what a “block device” is, just think of it as a fancy "
"way to say “something that stores data”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:11
#: f30cf07d9a564708b2d6cbc050e9504a
msgid "Using the Devices Widget to Attach a Drive"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:14
#: 9b91412c4a814fc195697144307124f7
msgid ""
"(**Note:** In the present context, the term “USB drive” denotes any `USB "
"mass storage device "
"<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USB_mass_storage_device_class>`__. In "
"addition to smaller flash memory sticks, this includes things like USB "
"external hard drives.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:16
#: de5aaecd7fe04dc3ad2907b1a3c2fd19
msgid ""
"Qubes OS supports the ability to attach a USB drive (or just its "
"partitions) to any qube easily, no matter which qube handles the USB "
"controller."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:18
#: ebdc6fe5ecb4469daa899da9d0533860
msgid ""
"Attaching USB drives is integrated into the Devices Widget: |device "
"manager icon| Simply insert your USB drive and click on the widget. You "
"will see multiple entries for your USB drive; typically, ``sys-usb:sda``,"
" ``sys-usb:sda1``, and ``sys-usb:2-1`` for example. Entries starting with"
" a number (e.g. here ``2-1``) are the :doc:`whole usb-device </user/how-"
"to-guides/how-to-use-usb-devices>`. Entries without a number (e.g. here "
"``sda``) are the whole block-device. Other entries are partitions of that"
" block-device (e.r. here ``sda1``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:282
#: 677c351aecc140438d26687964951b96 7ece0c3b82234fa8a20a69668aa11443
msgid "device manager icon"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:20
#: 0c44cd7e98fe49178e2f2748cc01a9ea
msgid ""
"The simplest option is to attach the entire block drive. In our example, "
"this is ``sys-usb:sda``, so hover over it. This will pop up a submenu "
"showing running VMs to which the USB drive can be connected. Click on one"
" and your USB drive will be attached!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:22
#: 5e0ef8c479bd4ddd9395fa98e050782a
msgid ""
"**Note:** attaching individual partitions (e.g. ``sys-usb:sda1``) can be "
"slightly more secure because it doesn’t force the target app qube to "
"parse the partition table. However, it often means the app qube won’t "
"detect the new partition and you will need to manually mount it inside "
"the app qube. See below for more detailed steps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:25
#: 64e1b5e9a3c94d42b3e078c68bdd19f9
msgid "Block Devices in VMs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:28
#: fe2a117b77314c94af9ffd9d67d16709
msgid ""
"If not specified otherwise, block devices will show up as ``/dev/xvdi*`` "
"in a linux VM, where ``*`` may be the partition-number. If a block device"
" isn’t automatically mounted after attaching, open a terminal in the VM "
"and execute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:38
#: 6bf84a0c94b54a97a3588ea3d08c7594
msgid ""
"where ``xvdi2`` needs to be replaced with the partition you want to "
"mount. This will make your drive content accessible under ``~/mnt``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:40
#: e879e99e0c1746d89009821ad0335dbb
msgid ""
"Beware that when you attach a whole block device, partitions can be "
"identified by their trailing integer (i.e. ``/dev/xvdi2`` for the second "
"partition, ``/dev/xvdi`` for the whole device), whereas if you attach a "
"single partition, the partition has *no trailing integer*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:42
#: 4fcdfda1f11540429805904454d4dd5f
msgid ""
"If several different block-devices are attached to a single VM, the last "
"letter of the device node name is advanced through the alphabet, so after"
" ``xvdi`` the next device will be named ``xvdj``, the next ``xvdk``, and "
"so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:44
#: 6d8d2cc88bbc4eaca27258b30c74288e
msgid ""
"To specify this device node name, you need to use the command line tool "
"and its `frontend-dev-option <#frontend-dev>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:47
#: 9a6abaf7fafe4304b6ddc5a641ba200a
msgid "Command Line Tool Guide"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:50
#: 68232d3c5ba24a4c86dbaab090c0daa9
msgid ""
"The command-line tool you may use to mount whole USB drives or their "
"partitions is ``qvm-block``, a shortcut for ``qvm-device block``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:52
#: fca8ecfa76784da5b6bef7d004b68836
msgid ""
"``qvm-block`` won’t recognise your device by any given name, but rather "
"the device-node the sourceVM assigns. So make sure you have the drive "
"available in the sourceVM, then list the available block devices (step "
"1.) to find the corresponding device-node."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-block-storage-devices.rst:54
#: c52d658e55ed4b23af9e929be42140a9
msgid ""
"In case of a USB-drive, make sure it’s attached to your computer. If you "
"don’t see anything that looks like your drive, run ``sudo udevadm trigger"
" --action=change`` in your USB-qube (typically ``sys-usb``)"
msgstr ""

